  "meta": {
    "title": "Ocean Microbiome: Vertical Stratification Epi to Mesopelagic",
    "date": "2026-07-18",
    "lesson": "Global surveys of ocean microbes reveal that communities are vertically stratified: the sunlit epipelagic zone hosts a distinct set of microbial taxa compared to the darker, colder mesopelagic below. Within the epipelagic zone itself, temperature is the dominant factor shaping which microbes thrive, outweighing other environmental gradients or even geographic distance between sample sites. This means two far-apart surface samples at similar temperatures can look more alike than two nearby samples separated by a thermocline. Large-scale gene cataloguing of viruses, prokaryotes, and picoeukaryotes shows enormous novel genetic diversity, but a shared 'core' set of functions recurs across the ocean and even overlaps substantially with gut microbiomes, suggesting some metabolic functions are broadly favored across very different habitats. In this level, cells must adapt to a temperature-stratified water column, competing for particulate organic matter using enzymes tuned to their depth niche.",
    "citation": "Sunagawa, Coelho, Chaffron (2015). Structure and function of the global ocean microbiome. doi:10.1126/science.1261359",
    "difficulty": "normal",
    "realWorldBasis": "Tara Oceans metagenomics: epipelagic vs mesopelagic vertical stratification driven by temperature"
  },
